To attack these arguments directly would be at once easy and futile. Every age must interpret the course of history in accordance with its own deepest reflections upon the meaning of the world. It is this alone which gives value to each fresh interpretation, and only when he pre- tends to be master of a positive and unalterable science does the historiari become an impostor. The real difficulties of Dante’s position will, therefore, best be exhibited, not by disputing his inferences from history, but by putting to him a direct question which he never puts to‘ himself. What is meant by the populus Romanus? It is idle to refer merely to ancient history, for Dante's object is to dictate a policy to his contemporaries, and the whole tenor of the second book forbids us to think any longer of the Emperor as an isolated official, who exercises jurisdiction over all nations, but himself belongs to none.

· He is, on the contrary, the head of a people which rules ,the world by right of conquest. Equally impossible is ¹it to suppose that, because the imperial authority knows no boundaries, the populus Romanus must embrace all man- * kind. For that would deprive of all meaning the story of its victory in the struggle. Conquest may in some sense absorb the whole human race, but the Romans are none the less a peculiar people.
